  "response_text": "A good post-workout meal for building muscle should include a combination of protein, carbohydrates, and healthy fats to promote recovery and muscle growth. Here are some options:\n\n1. **Grilled Chicken with Quinoa and Vegetables**:\n   - **Protein**: Grilled chicken breast\n   - **Carbohydrates**: Quinoa\n   - **Fats**: Olive oil drizzled on vegetables\n\n2. **Greek Yogurt with Berries and Nuts**:\n   - **Protein**: Greek yogurt\n   - **Carbohydrates**: Fresh berries (e.g., blueberries, strawberries)\n   - **Fats**: A handful of nuts (e.g., almonds, walnuts)\n\n3. **Salmon with Sweet Potato and Asparagus**:\n   - **Protein**: Grilled or baked salmon\n   - **Carbohydrates**: Baked sweet potato\n   - **Fats**: Olive oil or avocado on asparagus\n\n4. **Egg Omelette with Spinach and Whole Grain Toast**:\n   - **Protein**: Eggs\n   - **Carbohydrates**: Whole grain toast\n   - **Fats**: Avocado or cheese in the omelette\n\n5. **Protein Smoothie**:\n   - **Protein**: Protein powder (whey, pea, or other)\n   - **Carbohydrates**: Banana or oats blended in\n   - **Fats**: Nut butter or chia seeds\n\n6. **Cottage Cheese with Pineapple and Flaxseeds**:\n   - **Protein**: Cottage cheese\n   - **Carbohydrates**: Pineapple chunks\n   - **Fats**: Flaxseeds or nuts\n\nAim to consume your post-workout meal within 30 to 60 minutes after exercising to optimize recovery. This meal should ideally have a ratio of about 3:1 or 4:1 of carbohydrates to protein for the best results in muscle recovery and growth. Additionally, staying hydrated is crucial, so be sure to drink water or a recovery drink if needed.",
